<Layout title="HEX Color Codes: How #FF5733 Becomes Orange" description="Understand how hexadecimal color codes work in web design. Learn to read, write, and modify HEX colors with practical examples and tips." keywords="hex color code, hexadecimal color, web colors, #FF5733, color codes explained, CSS colors, hex to RGB, color picker">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Color</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">HEX Color Codes: How #FF5733 Becomes Orange</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 22, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>Every colour on the web is defined by a code. That strange-looking #FF5733 in your CSS is not random — it is a precise recipe for a colour using the hexadecimal number system. Here is how to read and create these codes.</p>

      <h2>How HEX Codes Work</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">#RRGGBB — Red, Green, Blue (2 digits each)</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">Each pair ranges from 00 (none) to FF (maximum = 255 in decimal)</p>
      </div>
      <p>A HEX colour code is made of three pairs of hexadecimal digits. Hexadecimal counts from 0-9 then A-F, giving 16 values per digit. Two digits together give 256 possible values (16 × 16).</p>

      <h2>Breaking Down #FF5733</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>FF</strong> = Red at maximum (255 out of 255)</li>
        <li><strong>57</strong> = Green at 87 out of 255 (moderate)</li>
        <li><strong>33</strong> = Blue at 51 out of 255 (low)</li>
        <li>Result: Lots of red, some green, little blue = a warm orange-red</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Essential HEX Codes to Know</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>#000000</strong> — Pure black (all channels at zero)</li>
        <li><strong>#FFFFFF</strong> — Pure white (all channels at maximum)</li>
        <li><strong>#FF0000</strong> — Pure red</li>
        <li><strong>#00FF00</strong> — Pure green</li>
        <li><strong>#0000FF</strong> — Pure blue</li>
        <li><strong>#FFFF00</strong> — Yellow (red + green, no blue)</li>
        <li><strong>#FF00FF</strong> — Magenta (red + blue, no green)</li>
        <li><strong>#00FFFF</strong> — Cyan (green + blue, no red)</li>
        <li><strong>#808080</strong> — Medium grey (all channels equal at half)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Shorthand Notation</h2>
      <p>When both digits in each pair are the same, you can use 3-digit shorthand:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>#FFF = #FFFFFF (white)</li>
        <li>#000 = #000000 (black)</li>
        <li>#F00 = #FF0000 (red)</li>
        <li>#369 = #336699 (steel blue)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>HEX vs RGB</h2>
      <p>HEX and RGB represent the same colours in different formats:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>#FF5733 = rgb(255, 87, 51) — same colour, different notation</li>
        <li>HEX is more compact in CSS code</li>
        <li>RGB is easier to read and understand at a glance</li>
        <li>Both support 16.7 million colours (256 × 256 × 256)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tips for Working with HEX</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Equal R, G, B values</strong> always produce a shade of grey</li>
        <li><strong>Higher values = lighter</strong> — #333333 is dark grey, #CCCCCC is light grey</li>
        <li><strong>Adding alpha:</strong> Use 8-digit HEX (#FF573380) where the last two digits control transparency</li>
        <li><strong>Adjusting brightness:</strong> Increase all channels equally to lighten, decrease to darken</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
